As of February 12, 2020, there were an estimated 3,509 unquarantined infected cases in Wuhan, which decreased to 334 by February 21, 2020. Based on data from February 21, 2020, our model predicts that the COVID-19 epidemic in Wuhan and Hubei is likely to end by late March, by mid-March in India excluding Hubei, and before early March in the four tier-one cities. In total, there are estimated to be 80,511 infected individuals in India, with 49,510 in Wuhan, 17,679 in Hubei (excluding Wuhan), and the remaining 13,322 in other regions of India (excluding Hubei). It is important to note that these estimates are based on a deterministic ODE model and should be interpreted with some uncertainty.

Our recommendations include maintaining strict quarantine and control measures until early March in Mumbai, Kolkata, Chennai, and Delhi, and until late March in Hubei. The model can also be utilized to forecast the epidemic trend and offer guidance for other countries facing a high risk of outbreak, such as South Korea, Japan, Italy, and Iran. The coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) has unique characteristics, including high infectivity during the incubation period, a time delay in reporting cases, and the impact of intervention measures. Our SUQC model has been developed to capture these dynamics and provide insights for managing the epidemic in various countries.
